{
  "root": {
    "children": [
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Today in “",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 0,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": "I told you so",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              }
            ],
            "direction": "ltr",
            "format": "",
            "indent": 0,
            "type": "link",
            "rel": null,
            "target": null,
            "title": null,
            "url": "__GHOST_URL__/2020/03/why-we-need-more-than-just-good-coronavirus-reporting-right-now/",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "”:",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "bookmark",
        "url": "https://www.wired.com/story/coronavirus-news-fatigue-is-officially-setting-in/",
        "metadata": {
          "url": "https://www.wired.co.uk/article/coronavirus-news-fatigue",
          "title": "Coronavirus News Fatigue Is Officially Setting In",
          "description": "News fatigue isn’t new. But it could indicate problematic changes in our behavior with respect to the pandemic.",
          "author": "Will Bedingfield, WIRED UK",
          "publisher": "WIRED",
          "thumbnail": "https://media.wired.com/photos/5e99db6fd42e6f0008f47b5d/191:100/w_1280,c_limit/Cul-handshadow-3137893.jpg",
          "icon": "https://www.wired.com/verso/static/wired/assets/favicon.ccc13c90b928e0b02eaafcfb05864c93a0136dd0.ico"
        }
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Yes, the huge coronabump in traffic seems to be on the decline. March's record traffic figures to Covid-19 related stories have not continued into April for many publications. ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "By the end of March this attention had ebbed, continuing its downward slope in the first week of April, before falling to pretty much normal levels this week. It seems we may have developed coronavirus news fatigue. But why has this happened? Could people really be losing interest in such a cataclysmic event? And what does this drop-off mean for government strategy?",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "quote",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "There's some interesting insight from Richard Bentall, a professor of clinical psychology at the University of Sheffield, in the ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "WIRED",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " piece:",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "People, explains Bentall, tend to be classified into “monitors” and ”blunters.” The former tend to search for more information when anxious; the latter tend to block it out. “This is speculation, but what we might be seeing is the population sorting itself out into these two different groups,” he says.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "quote",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Well, perhaps. But perhaps it might be more useful to think that we are all a mix of the two characteristics. Journalists, on the whole, tend to bias very much towards the \"monitors\" end of the spectrum - and they can have problems empathising with those who don't - a tenency everyone who works in audience development will be familair with. That's why every article had to have a coronavirus intro a few weeks ago - and why, I might suggest, they are prone to misinterpreting this shift in attention. ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Distraction > Good News",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "koenig-heading",
        "tag": "h2",
        "version": 1,
        "renderVersion": "3.0"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "In a predictably good piece, Mathew Ingram, looks at the ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 0,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": "sudden trend towards Good News",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              }
            ],
            "direction": "ltr",
            "format": "",
            "indent": 0,
            "type": "link",
            "rel": null,
            "target": null,
            "title": null,
            "url": "https://mailchi.mp/atlanticmedia/publishers-expand-good-news-offerings?e=2c33cb88bf",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " as an antidote to wall-to-wall Covid-19 coverage:",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "But a focus on only good news could easily turn into escapism, if it involves deliberately avoiding the truth in favor of something that feels better, because it implies that the world is just fine the way it is, and therefore nothing needs to change.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "quote",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "bookmark",
        "url": "https://www.cjr.org/the_media_today/good-news-uplifting-delusional.php",
        "metadata": {
          "url": "https://www.cjr.org/the_media_today/good-news-uplifting-delusional.php",
          "title": "The good-news trend: Uplifting? Delusional? Both?",
          "description": "<p>Since we are currently in a global pandemic that has caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people and the closure of stores, restaurants, and other hallmarks of normal life, it’s not surprising many people are searching for things to take their minds off the gloom. And what they are clinging …",
          "author": "Mathew Ingram",
          "publisher": "Columbia Journalism Review",
          "thumbnail": "https://cdn.cjr.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/cjr-themediatoday-03b-800x419.jpg?122376",
          "icon": "https://cdn.cjr.org/wp-content/themes/cjr2017/_resources2015/img/favicon-152.png"
        }
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "I do wonder if Mathew is over-thinking it, though. I think the shift towards \"good news\" ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "is",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " a mistake, but only because what people are ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "actually",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " after is distraction, not relentless positivity, which is just as wearing as relentless negativity. It's very typical of journalism to bounce from one extreme to another: \"relentless horror\" to \"cheery upbeat\". There's a whole bunch of interesting middle-ground between them that's not coronavirus-flavoured. And, again, it's symptomatic of a struggle within journalists to understand people who ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "aren't",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " news-obsesssed. ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "I may be atypical of many journalists in this. I recognised that I had a hard limit on how much Covid-19 coverage I could take early on, and made an active effort to seek out other things I could read. I even ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 0,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": "(re)launched a Covid-19-free newsletter",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              }
            ],
            "direction": "ltr",
            "format": "",
            "indent": 0,
            "type": "link",
            "rel": null,
            "target": null,
            "title": null,
            "url": "http://www.engagedreadingtime.com",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " to help myself do that. But it's not a newsletter about \"good news\" - it's a newsletter about ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "other things. ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "And it's nice to see ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The Telegraph",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " following my lead… 😉",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "bookmark",
        "url": "http://m.email3.telegraph.co.uk/nl/jsp/m.jsp?c=%40j5kP3h5DGV2cWCI4fz7rOEjpNpvEReTqFdtInEsUD1o%3D&WT&WT.mc_id=e_DM1235126&WT.tsrc=email&etype=Loy_Dig_Acq_200414_InOtherNewsNL_1&utmsource=email&utm_medium=Loy_Dig_Acq_200414_InOtherNewsNL_120200414&utm_campaign=DM1235126",
        "metadata": {
          "url": "http://m.email3.telegraph.co.uk/nl/jsp/m.jsp?c=%40j5kP3h5DGV2cWCI4fz7rOM06wqfkSoTF5sq9EWlzev4%3D",
          "title": "Welcome to In Other News: Telegraph highlights with no mention of the c-word",
          "description": "Including Killing Eve’s new writer with a taste of season three, and some of Princess Diana’s best looks",
          "author": null,
          "publisher": null,
          "thumbnail": "https://www.telegraph.co.uk/content/dam/emailing/Editorialnewsletterthumbnails/utilities-default-newsletter.png",
          "icon": null
        }
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "And journalists are far from alone in this. Marketeers appear to be having similar issues: ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "embed",
        "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vM3J9jDoaTA&feature=emb_title",
        "html": "<iframe width=\"480\" height=\"270\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/vM3J9jDoaTA?feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen></iframe>",
        "embedType": "video"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The fundemental question many editors should be asking is: “how can we usefully and profitably distract our readers with intreresting and useful journalism?” not “what good news should we publish?”.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "That might prove more productive than all piling into the Good News trend. ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalrule"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The Long Read",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "koenig-heading",
        "tag": "h2",
        "version": 1,
        "renderVersion": "3.0"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "A good piece by Jeff Jarvis exploring the challenge of doing science (and science-adjacent, which pretty much all coronavirus coverage is) journalism when the science of Covid-19 is being explored publicly by scientists. ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The role of journalists ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "must",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " change in an era where the experts can publish for themselves, and there's some interesting questions raised here about what that role should be - and how we establish expertise in those we choose to amplify. ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "bookmark",
        "url": "https://medium.com/whither-news/the-open-information-ecosystem-6dfd7d7b47a5",
        "metadata": {
          "url": "https://medium.com/whither-news/the-open-information-ecosystem-6dfd7d7b47a5",
          "title": "The Open Information Ecosystem",
          "description": "Media are no longer the deliverers of information. The information has already been delivered. So the question now for journalists is how — and whether — we add value to that stream of information…",
          "author": "Jeff Jarvis",
          "publisher": "Whither news?",
          "thumbnail": "https://miro.medium.com/max/1200/1*gP-LEyABRqRVZTITWnRNGg.png",
          "icon": "https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/fit/c/152/152/1*8I-HPL0bfoIzGied-dzOvA.png"
        }
      },
